"Zhang T., Frauenfeld O.W., Serreze M.C., Etringer A., Oelke C., McCreight J., Barry R.G., Gilichinsky D., Yang D., Ye H., Ling F., Chudinova S.","Spatial and temporal variability in active layer thickness over the Russian Arctic drainage basin",2005,"Journal of Geophysical Research D: Atmospheres","110","16", D16101,"1","14",,,10.1029/2004JD005642,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-26444506202&partnerID=40&md5=b2bba87e3ecc587b7754e2c3761b0583","National Snow and Ice Data Center, Cooperative Institute for Research in Environmental Sciences, University of Colorado, Boulder, CO 80309-0449, United States; Institute for Geophysics, University of Münster, J-48149 Münster, Germany; Institute for Physiochemical and Biological Problems in Soil Science, Russian Academy of Sciences, 142290 Pushchino, Moscow Region, Russian Federation; Water and Environmental Research Center, University of Alaska, Fairbanks, AK 99775, United States; Department of Geography and Urban Analysis, California State University, Los Angeles, CA 90032-8222, United States; Department of Computer Science and Technology, Zhaoqing University, Zhaoqing, Guangdong Province 526061, China","Zhang, T., National Snow and Ice Data Center, Cooperative Institute for Research in Environmental Sciences, University of Colorado, Boulder, CO 80309-0449, United States; Frauenfeld, O.W., National Snow and Ice Data Center, Cooperative Institute for Research in Environmental Sciences, University of Colorado, Boulder, CO 80309-0449, United States; Serreze, M.C., National Snow and Ice Data Center, Cooperative Institute for Research in Environmental Sciences, University of Colorado, Boulder, CO 80309-0449, United States; Etringer, A., National Snow and Ice Data Center, Cooperative Institute for Research in Environmental Sciences, University of Colorado, Boulder, CO 80309-0449, United States; Oelke, C., Institute for Geophysics, University of Münster, J-48149 Münster, Germany; McCreight, J., National Snow and Ice Data Center, Cooperative Institute for Research in Environmental Sciences, University of Colorado, Boulder, CO 80309-0449, United States; Barry, R.G., National Snow and Ice Data Center, Cooperative Institute for Research in Environmental Sciences, University of Colorado, Boulder, CO 80309-0449, United States; Gilichinsky, D., Institute for Physiochemical and Biological Problems in Soil Science, Russian Academy of Sciences, 142290 Pushchino, Moscow Region, Russian Federation; Yang, D., Water and Environmental Research Center, University of Alaska, Fairbanks, AK 99775, United States; Ye, H., Department of Geography and Urban Analysis, California State University, Los Angeles, CA 90032-8222, United States; Ling, F., Department of Computer Science and Technology, Zhaoqing University, Zhaoqing, Guangdong Province 526061, China; Chudinova, S., Institute for Physiochemical and Biological Problems in Soil Science, Russian Academy of Sciences, 142290 Pushchino, Moscow Region, Russian Federation","Changes in active layer thickness (ALT) over northern high-latitude permafrost regions have important impacts on the surface energy balance, hydrologic cycle, carbon exchange between the atmosphere and the land surface, plant growth, and ecosystems as a whole. This study examines the 20th century variations of ALT for the Ob, Yenisey, and Lena River basins. ALT is estimated from historical soil temperature measurements from 17 stations (1956-1990, Lena basin only), an annual thawing index based on both surface air temperature data (1901-2002) and numerical modeling (1980-2002). The latter two provide spatial fields. Based on the thawing index, the long-term average (1961-1990) ALT is about 1.87 m in the Ob, 1.67 in the Yenisey, and 1.69 m in the Lena basin. Over the past several decades, ALT over the three basins shows positive trends, but with different magnitudes. Based on the 17 stations, ALT increased about 0.32 m between 1956 and 1990 in the Lena. To the extent that results based on the soil temperatures represent ground ""truth,"" ALT obtained from both the thawing index and numerical modeling is underestimated. It is widely believed that ALT will increase with global warming. However, this hypothesis needs further refinement since ALT responds primarily to summer air temperature while observed warming has occurred mainly in winter and spring. It is also shown that ALT exhibits complex and inconsistent responses to variations in snow cover. Copyright 2005 by the American Geophysical Union.",,"climate change; drainage basin; global warming; numerical model; permafrost; spatiotemporal analysis; time series analysis; Eastern Hemisphere; Eurasia; Russian Federation; World",,,,,,"Armstrong, R.L., Historical Soviet daily snow depth, version 2 (2001), http://nsidc.org, [CD-ROM], Natl. Snow and Ice Data Cent., Boulder, Colo. (Available at)Armstrong, R.L., Brodzik, M.J., An earth-gridded SSM/I data set for cryospheric studies and global change monitoring (1995) Adv. Space Res., 16 (10), pp. 155-163; Armstrong, R.L., Brodzik, M.J., Recent Northern Hemisphere snow extent: A comparison of data derived from visible and microwave satellite sensors (2001) Geophys. Res. Lett., 28 (19), pp. 3673-3676; Armstrong, R.L., Brodzik, M.J., Northern Hemisphere EASE-Grid weekly snow cover and sea ice extent, version 2 (2002), [CD-ROM], Natl. Snow and Ice Data Cent., Boulder, ColoGlossary of permafrost and related ground-ice terms (1988), Associate Committee on Geotechnical Research Tech. Memo. 142, Natl. Res. Counc. of Can., Ottawa, Ont., CanBockheim, J.G., Everett, L.R., Hinkel, K.M., Fritts, F.E., Brown, J., Soil organic carbon and distribution in arctic tundra, Barrow, Alaska (1999) Soil Sci. Soc. Am. J., 63, pp. 934-940; Brown, J., Loveland, T.R., Merchant, J.W., Reed, B.C., Ohlen, D.O., Using multisource data in global land cover characterization: Concepts, requirements, and methods (1993) Photogramm. Eng. Remote Sens., 59, pp. 977-987; Brown, J., Ferrian